00:35:51,024 --> 00:35:52,025
Ms. Han.

512
00:35:52,859 --> 00:35:55,903
Could you make a copy
of Ms. Jeong Sunja's case file

513
00:35:55,904 --> 00:35:58,657
- and submit a request for visitation?
- Yes, of course.

514
00:36:01,743 --> 00:36:03,828
Could you pull up
defendant's Exhibit 5, please?

515
00:36:06,706 --> 00:36:07,706
STANDARD RENTAL AGREEMENT

516
00:36:07,707 --> 00:36:12,252
These are the contracts signed by tenants
living in the plaintiff's building.

517
00:36:12,253 --> 00:36:13,712
As you can see,

518
00:36:13,713 --> 00:36:17,007
every one of these leases
was signed through the real estate office.

519
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:19,177
Could you pull up
defendant's Exhibit 6, please?

520
00:36:21,930 --> 00:36:22,930
Thank you.

521
00:36:22,931 --> 00:36:24,015
POWER OF ATTORNEY

522
00:36:26,851 --> 00:36:28,686
GRANTOR
HEO SIWON

523
00:36:28,687 --> 00:36:31,939
As you can see,
only the date section was left blank

524
00:36:31,940 --> 00:36:34,234
and was later filled in by hand.

525
00:36:34,943 --> 00:36:36,402
This was the case for all of them.

526
00:36:36,403 --> 00:36:38,570
The plaintiff gave

527
00:36:38,571 --> 00:36:42,449
dozens of POA documents stamped
with his seal to the real estate office

528
00:36:42,450 --> 00:36:45,411
and told them to fill in the dates
and use as needed.

529
00:36:45,412 --> 00:36:48,706
Even after ending
their business relationship,

530
00:36:48,707 --> 00:36:51,458
the plaintiff did not take back
the rest of those documents.

531
00:36:51,459 --> 00:36:55,462
So the defendant saw
one of those stamped documents

532
00:36:55,463 --> 00:36:58,967
and believed the realtor
still had power of attorney.

533
00:36:59,634 --> 00:37:01,552
Since the plaintiff
is partly responsible

534
00:37:01,553 --> 00:37:03,178
for the defendant's misunderstanding,

535
00:37:03,179 --> 00:37:05,723
according to Civil Act, Article 129,

536
00:37:05,724 --> 00:37:08,727
the defendant's lease
should be carried out as normal.

537
00:37:09,769 --> 00:37:10,894
Plaintiff's counsel,

538
00:37:10,895 --> 00:37:13,564
is it true the landlord
didn't take back those documents?

539
00:37:13,565 --> 00:37:15,774
He heard the realtor
had destroyed all of them.

540
00:37:15,775 --> 00:37:18,902
So he heard
but didn't personally take them back?

541
00:37:18,903 --> 00:37:20,904
Yes, Your Honor.
That is my understanding.

542
00:37:20,905 --> 00:37:22,407
Here's what we'll do.

543
00:37:23,324 --> 00:37:26,952
I'm issuing a settlement recommendation.

544
00:37:26,953 --> 00:37:29,038
Let's have the plaintiff
withdraw the lawsuit,

545
00:37:29,539 --> 00:37:34,418
and I'll send out the official decision
to have the lease agreement carried out.

546
00:37:34,419 --> 00:37:37,589
Counsel, meet with the plaintiff
and try to convince him.

547
00:37:38,673 --> 00:37:40,133
The plaintiff is a victim too.

548
00:37:41,509 --> 00:37:43,093
And so is the defendant.

549
00:37:43,094 --> 00:37:45,637
If the plaintiff played a part
in causing this situation,

550
00:37:45,638 --> 00:37:48,850
then Civil Act Article 129 says
he bears responsibility.

551
00:37:49,434 --> 00:37:50,477
Yes, Your Honor.

552
00:37:51,186 --> 00:37:52,644
- Defense counsel.
- Yes, Your Honor?

553
00:37:52,645 --> 00:37:55,689
You understand that if we go
with a settlement recommendation,

554
00:37:55,690 --> 00:37:59,568
each party will cover
their own legal fees?

555
00:37:59,569 --> 00:38:01,737
- Yes, Your Honor.
- The plaintiff can't be ordered

556
00:38:01,738 --> 00:38:03,989
to pay the defendant's fees.

557
00:38:03,990 --> 00:38:05,492
Are you okay with that?

558
00:38:08,369 --> 00:38:10,162
- Yes, Your Honor.
- Okay.

559
00:38:10,163 --> 00:38:13,624
Then, I'll issue the decision
on the settlement recommendation.

560
00:38:13,625 --> 00:38:16,668
If there are no objections
within two weeks, it'll be finalized.

561
00:38:16,669 --> 00:38:17,753
Thank you, everyone.

562
00:38:17,754 --> 00:38:20,381
Let's move on to the next case.

563
00:38:40,860 --> 00:38:42,195
Attorney Ha.

564
00:38:45,073 --> 00:38:46,074
Thank you.

565
00:38:46,658 --> 00:38:49,577
Thank you so much, Attorney Ha.

566
00:38:50,703 --> 00:38:53,247
You're very lucky. I told you.

567
00:38:53,248 --> 00:38:55,041
You're a very lucky person, Yunsu.

568
00:38:58,294 --> 00:38:59,712
Thank you, Attorney Ha.

569
00:39:02,632 --> 00:39:04,968
Aren't you hungry?
Do you want to go get some food?

570
00:39:07,053 --> 00:39:08,054
Let's go.

571
00:39:16,187 --> 00:39:17,856
Slowly. Okay.

572
00:39:31,911 --> 00:39:32,996
Attorney Ha.

573
00:39:34,497 --> 00:39:35,915
You're so cool.

574
00:39:37,208 --> 00:39:38,250
Sorry?

575
00:39:38,251 --> 00:39:40,003
You took care of everything.

576
00:39:41,170 --> 00:39:44,799
I want to go to college too
and become just like you.

577
00:39:45,842 --> 00:39:48,719
Then, are you studying right now?

578
00:39:48,720 --> 00:39:51,264
Yes, I've been preparing
for the college entrance exam.

579
00:39:53,016 --> 00:39:54,141
But I may have to stop now.

580
00:39:54,142 --> 00:39:55,268
Why?

581
00:39:56,311 --> 00:39:58,313
Well, I need to make money.

582
00:39:59,314 --> 00:40:02,525
I have a younger sibling
who's about to age out of the orphanage.

583
00:40:03,234 --> 00:40:04,819
I'll have to take care of them.

584
00:40:06,404 --> 00:40:08,239
My situation may not allow me to study.

585
00:40:17,582 --> 00:40:18,583
Well...

586
00:40:20,335 --> 00:40:22,003
Even if you can't right now,

587
00:40:23,546 --> 00:40:27,008
don't give up on your dream completely.

588
00:40:30,970 --> 00:40:32,305
These are all cooked.

589
00:40:40,521 --> 00:40:41,522
Thank you.

590
00:40:48,529 --> 00:40:51,658
Can you check if we still have
that scholarship certificate?

591
00:40:52,450 --> 00:40:53,451
Yeah.

592
00:40:54,369 --> 00:40:56,329
No, it's probably with you.

593
00:40:57,747 --> 00:41:00,583
No, there's just someone
I want to connect the scholarship with.

594
00:41:01,334 --> 00:41:04,045
Okay. All right, bye.

595
00:41:26,693 --> 00:41:28,610
- Have you thought it over?
- About what?

596
00:41:28,611 --> 00:41:30,028
Joining the company.

597
00:41:30,029 --> 00:41:32,114
I'm not doing it. It's not for me.

598
00:41:32,115 --> 00:41:33,573
And being a lawyer is?

599
00:41:33,574 --> 00:41:36,118
Even if I quit law,
I'm not going into business.

600
00:41:36,119 --> 00:41:39,496
If I'd been interested,
I would've joined from the start.

601
00:41:39,497 --> 00:41:42,709
It's not like I got into business
because I loved it.

602
00:41:43,334 --> 00:41:46,086
You're drawn to
what suits you as you go.

603
00:41:46,087 --> 00:41:48,755
I didn't start law
because I loved it either.

604
00:41:48,756 --> 00:41:51,717
But I'll figure out what suits me as I go.

605
00:41:51,718 --> 00:41:53,010
You stubborn kid.

606
00:41:53,011 --> 00:41:55,054
You get that from me, you know.

607
00:41:55,555 --> 00:41:56,680
I know.

608
00:41:56,681 --> 00:41:58,641
That's why you'd do well in business.

609
00:41:59,726 --> 00:42:00,727
For goodness' sake.

610
00:42:02,562 --> 00:42:04,730
- I have plans too.
- What plans?

611
00:42:04,731 --> 00:42:06,231
Just wait.

612
00:42:06,232 --> 00:42:07,900
I have something I'm working on.

613
00:42:11,487 --> 00:42:14,449
MATERIALS TO PREPARE FOR PROSECUTOR EXAM

614
00:42:24,333 --> 00:42:25,709
<i>What about beyond that stream?</i>

615
00:42:25,710 --> 00:42:27,378
No, that's not part of it.

616
00:42:33,676 --> 00:42:36,053
<i>He was full of nonsense all along.</i>

617
00:42:36,054 --> 00:42:38,972
<i>Either the old man was mistaken or lying.</i>

618
00:42:38,973 --> 00:42:42,225
If he wasn't around in our town,
nothing would get done.

619
00:42:42,226 --> 00:42:44,520
Come on.

620
00:42:46,564 --> 00:42:49,233
Do you feel bad for the old man?

621
00:42:49,984 --> 00:42:52,862
<i>I wanted Mr. Park Mansu
to be telling the truth.</i>

622
00:42:53,780 --> 00:42:55,739
<i>Even the part
about doing it out of goodwill.</i>

623
00:42:55,740 --> 00:42:58,826
Do you only do things for your gain?

624
00:43:00,328 --> 00:43:01,829
If I don't do this, who will?

625
00:43:02,955 --> 00:43:06,125
Someone's got to do it,
so that's why I'm doing it.

626
00:43:14,467 --> 00:43:16,761
<i>It looked like a document
from the National Archives.</i>

627
00:43:18,096 --> 00:43:19,763
As if you've ever been there before.

628
00:43:19,764 --> 00:43:21,389
- Have you?
- Of course, I have.

629
00:43:21,390 --> 00:43:24,644
I once had a case
involving a national honoree.

630
00:43:37,615 --> 00:43:39,866
We can access
the National Archives these days, right?

631
00:43:39,867 --> 00:43:41,118
What?

632
00:43:41,119 --> 00:43:42,202
LOCATION NAME SEARCH

633
00:43:42,203 --> 00:43:45,206
"580 Dongjan-ri."

634
00:43:45,873 --> 00:43:46,873
Here.

635
00:43:46,874 --> 00:43:49,752
- Click on the one that says "Han Insu."
- Okay.

636
00:43:51,546 --> 00:43:54,715
Let's pull everything
with the name "Han Insu" on it.

637
00:43:55,883 --> 00:43:57,468
Yeah, okay.

638
00:43:59,137 --> 00:44:01,806
Back then, Lot 580 was
one large piece of land.

639
00:44:02,890 --> 00:44:05,184
But it looks different
from how Mr. Park described it.

640
00:44:24,704 --> 00:44:26,789
- This part?
- Right?

641
00:44:37,216 --> 00:44:39,093
I'll print out
land registers for these areas.

642
00:44:46,893 --> 00:44:48,060
Eighty-four...

643
00:44:52,648 --> 00:44:53,649
Three-hundred eighty-four...

644
00:44:57,987 --> 00:44:59,655
One hundred and thirty...

645
00:45:08,414 --> 00:45:12,752
That's 130,757.1.

646
00:45:13,419 --> 00:45:14,503
And in acres...

647
00:45:15,463 --> 00:45:19,258
That adds up to around 32 acres.

648
00:45:20,051 --> 00:45:21,051
Here.

649
00:45:21,052 --> 00:45:25,348
That's around 32 acres.

650
00:45:26,265 --> 00:45:27,767
Mr. Park was right.

651
00:45:31,729 --> 00:45:33,105
Gosh.

652
00:46:09,767 --> 00:46:10,768
Hello.

653
00:46:11,435 --> 00:46:14,480
I'm Attorney Kang Huiji,
your court-appointed lawyer.

654
00:46:17,942 --> 00:46:18,943
Hello.

655
00:46:24,240 --> 00:46:26,450
Life in detention
is pretty tough, isn't it?

656
00:46:29,578 --> 00:46:31,622
I don't need a lawyer.

657
00:46:33,207 --> 00:46:36,126
I didn't even request a public defender.

658
00:46:36,127 --> 00:46:38,378
Who called you here?

659
00:46:38,379 --> 00:46:39,879
Ms. Jeong,

660
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:41,841
you fell under mandatory appointment.

661
00:46:42,842 --> 00:46:44,050
Even if you didn't apply,

662
00:46:44,051 --> 00:46:47,430
you were eligible to have the court
assign you an attorney.

663
00:46:50,433 --> 00:46:51,934
Then,

664
00:46:52,810 --> 00:46:55,104
just do whatever you have to do and go.

665
00:46:55,855 --> 00:46:57,565
Don't worry about me.

666
00:46:58,149 --> 00:46:59,400
My job

667
00:47:00,401 --> 00:47:02,736
is to hear your side of the story.

668
00:47:02,737 --> 00:47:05,822
It's to find out what happened and why.

669
00:47:05,823 --> 00:47:08,242
Hearing it won't change anything.

670
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:12,913
I killed Myeongjae...

671
00:47:15,750 --> 00:47:17,167
and I'll just take the punishment.

672
00:47:17,168 --> 00:47:20,170
Then, it'll be hard for the court
to understand your situation.

673
00:47:20,171 --> 00:47:21,839
I killed someone.

674
00:47:23,299 --> 00:47:25,217
What's there to understand?

675
00:47:28,304 --> 00:47:32,391
I don't want to be understood,
and I don't want to be forgiven either.

676
00:47:36,103 --> 00:47:39,398
- Just leave.
- I'm not here to understand you

677
00:47:40,858 --> 00:47:42,693
nor do I have the right to forgive you.

678
00:47:43,527 --> 00:47:46,906
Like you said, you'll be punished
no matter what your reasons are.

679
00:47:49,742 --> 00:47:50,743
Yes.

680
00:47:51,619 --> 00:47:52,703
Exactly.

681
00:47:53,829 --> 00:47:55,956
So make sure I get punished.

682
00:47:59,919 --> 00:48:01,629
If you have nothing else to say,

683
00:48:03,005 --> 00:48:04,215
may I go now?

684
00:48:37,665 --> 00:48:39,625
<i>I killed my brother.</i>

685
00:48:40,876 --> 00:48:42,294
<i>I'm the one who killed him.</i>

686
00:48:43,129 --> 00:48:44,672
<i>And I'll receive punishment.</i>

687
00:48:50,886 --> 00:48:53,555
LATE-ONSET DEMENTIA IN ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE

688
00:48:53,556 --> 00:48:55,182
DATE OF DIAGNOSIS
JUNE 7, 2015

689
00:48:58,602 --> 00:49:03,356
PHOTO OF CRIME SCENE

690
00:49:03,357 --> 00:49:04,817
Yes?

691
00:49:06,944 --> 00:49:10,239
Attorney Kang,
Ms. Jeong Sunja's children are here.

692
00:49:11,615 --> 00:49:12,741
Her children?

693
00:49:16,245 --> 00:49:19,622
Are you Ms. Jeong Sunja's son
and daughter?

694
00:49:19,623 --> 00:49:20,708
Yes.

695
00:49:22,334 --> 00:49:23,835
What's going to happen to her?

696
00:49:23,836 --> 00:49:25,713
She'll be going to trial soon.

697
00:49:26,505 --> 00:49:28,756
But she hasn't told me anything yet,

698
00:49:28,757 --> 00:49:31,510
so it's been difficult
to prepare her defense.

699
00:49:32,303 --> 00:49:35,389
How did she end up
living with her brother?

700
00:49:36,182 --> 00:49:38,058
I didn't know she had any children.

701
00:49:43,272 --> 00:49:44,273
Well...

702
00:49:45,232 --> 00:49:47,358
Our mom was the only family
our uncle had left.

703
00:49:47,359 --> 00:49:50,112
So she lived with him to take care of him.

704
00:49:51,906 --> 00:49:55,034
Then, did you two visit often?

705
00:49:56,744 --> 00:49:57,745
No.

706
00:49:58,746 --> 00:50:01,164
We didn't think it was something
we had to be involved in.

707
00:50:01,165 --> 00:50:04,126
How did Ms. Jeong manage financially?

708
00:50:05,044 --> 00:50:07,129
She likely had her pension

709
00:50:07,713 --> 00:50:10,257
and some caregiver support benefits.

710
00:50:10,841 --> 00:50:13,051
Did either of you
provide any financial help?

711
00:50:13,052 --> 00:50:14,345
No, we...

712
00:50:15,012 --> 00:50:16,889
We couldn't afford to do that.

713
00:50:18,849 --> 00:50:19,892
Can she get out?

714
00:50:25,981 --> 00:50:27,191
It's a murder charge.

715
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:30,277
It's not an easy situation to get out of.

716
00:50:31,987 --> 00:50:33,614
Gosh, Uncle Myeongjae...

717
00:50:35,699 --> 00:50:36,700
Would it...

718
00:50:37,993 --> 00:50:40,162
be okay if I visited where they stayed?

719
00:50:40,704 --> 00:50:43,082
- Hello?
<i>- Why did you call?</i>

720
00:50:43,916 --> 00:50:45,458
I have something to tell you.

721
00:50:45,459 --> 00:50:47,418
I wanted to ask if you could stop by.

722
00:50:47,419 --> 00:50:49,630
<i>Why call me in
if you won't take the case?</i>

723
00:50:50,256 --> 00:50:52,883
<i>I'm not going!
I'm busy looking for someone else.</i>

724
00:50:53,676 --> 00:50:56,762
We never said that.
We just said there wasn't enough evidence.

725
00:50:57,972 --> 00:51:00,391
Please come by.
It's something worth hearing.

726
00:51:03,310 --> 00:51:04,770
How about later at 5:00 p.m.?

727
00:51:05,604 --> 00:51:07,273
<i>We'll see if I have the time.</i>

728
00:51:08,023 --> 00:51:09,191
I'll see you later.

729
00:51:25,457 --> 00:51:26,709
You can go in.

730
00:51:27,293 --> 00:51:29,085
You're not coming in with me?

731
00:51:29,086 --> 00:51:30,169
No.

732
00:51:30,170 --> 00:51:32,464
We don't really feel like going in.

733
00:51:33,924 --> 00:51:35,259
Call us when you're done.

734
00:52:15,549 --> 00:52:20,596
ORAL MEDICATION

735
00:52:30,773 --> 00:52:32,107
MEDICAL RECEIPT

736
00:52:34,735 --> 00:52:37,863
<i>Tuesday, December 31st.</i>

737
00:52:38,822 --> 00:52:40,616
<i>No response at all.</i>

738
00:52:41,200 --> 00:52:43,284
<i>My chest felt heavy.</i>

739
00:52:43,285 --> 00:52:45,244
<i>His breathing grew shallow and rough.</i>

740
00:52:45,245 --> 00:52:46,371
<i>December 27th.</i>

741
00:52:46,372 --> 00:52:48,539
<i>He opened his eyes,
but they were glazed over.</i>

742
00:52:48,540 --> 00:52:50,291
<i>There was no reaction to my voice.</i>

743
00:52:50,292 --> 00:52:54,170
<i>I wish I could live
just one day longer than Myeongjae.</i>

744
00:52:54,171 --> 00:52:55,672
<i>December 25th.</i>

745
00:52:55,673 --> 00:52:57,423
<i>I called his name in the morning.</i>

746
00:52:57,424 --> 00:53:00,009
<i>He blinked and turned his head slightly.</i>

747
00:53:00,010 --> 00:53:03,221
<i>His eyes were clear for just a moment.</i>

748
00:53:03,222 --> 00:53:04,722
<i>He had a bit of porridge,</i>

749
00:53:04,723 --> 00:53:07,559
<i>and then slept a long time,
as if all his strength was gone.</i>

750
00:53:08,310 --> 00:53:09,852
<i>December 28th.</i>

751
00:53:09,853 --> 00:53:13,022
<i>He twitched slightly when I held his hand.</i>

752
00:53:13,023 --> 00:53:15,775
<i>His face looked peaceful,
and I felt more at ease.</i>

753
00:53:15,776 --> 00:53:16,901
<i>December 30th.</i>

754
00:53:16,902 --> 00:53:19,195
<i>I held his hand,
but there was no strength at all.</i>

755
00:53:19,196 --> 00:53:20,446
<i>I just kept the IV in.</i>

756
00:53:20,447 --> 00:53:23,908
<i>What am I hoping for
in trying to keep Myeongjae alive?</i>

757
00:53:23,909 --> 00:53:28,080
<i>Does he even want to live this way?</i>

758
00:53:29,498 --> 00:53:31,333
<i>December 29th.</i>

759
00:53:31,917 --> 00:53:33,793
<i>No response at all.</i>

760
00:53:33,794 --> 00:53:35,921
<i>He can barely swallow.</i>

761
00:53:38,382 --> 00:53:40,759
<i>No one's willing to hear me out.</i>

762
00:53:42,594 --> 00:53:44,888
<i>No one cares.</i>

763
00:53:53,897 --> 00:53:57,192
